1. Money and Time Value of Money (TVM)

Money today is worth more than the same amount in the future because it can be invested to earn returns.
This idea is the foundation of finance and explains concepts like interest, savings, loans, and investments.

Example: ₹1,000 today can become ₹1,100 next year with interest.

Key ideas: present value, future value, compounding.

2. Income, Saving, and Consumption

Income: Money earned from work, business, or investments.

Consumption: Money spent on goods and services.

Saving: Income not spent, set aside for future use.

A healthy financial system balances these three. High savings enable investment, which drives economic growth.

3. Investment

Investment means putting money into assets with the expectation of earning returns.

Common investment types:

Stocks (equity)

Bonds (debt)

Real estate

Mutual funds

Fixed deposits

All investments involve a trade-off between risk and return.

4. Risk and Return

Risk: Uncertainty about future returns.

Return: Gain or loss from an investment.

General rule:

Higher potential return → Higher risk
Lower risk → Lower return

Understanding risk helps investors make informed decisions.

5. Diversification

Diversification means not putting all your money in one place.

Investing in different assets reduces overall risk.

Losses in one investment may be offset by gains in another.

This principle is often summarized as:

“Don’t put all your eggs in one basket.”

6. Inflation

Inflation is the rise in prices over time, which reduces purchasing power.

If inflation is 6%, something costing ₹100 today will cost ₹106 next year.

Inflation affects savings, salaries, and investment returns.

Finance focuses on earning returns higher than inflation to grow real wealth.

7. Interest Rates

Interest is the cost of borrowing money or the reward for lending it.

Higher interest rates discourage borrowing and encourage saving.

Lower interest rates stimulate spending and investment.

Interest rates influence loans, deposits, bonds, and economic activity.

8. Credit and Debt

Credit: Ability to borrow money.

Debt: Money that must be repaid in the future.

Responsible use of credit can help build assets (education, business), while excessive debt can lead to financial stress.

9. Financial Markets

Financial markets connect borrowers and lenders.

Major types:

Stock markets

Bond markets

Money markets

Foreign exchange markets

They help allocate capital efficiently across the economy.

10. Budgeting and Financial Planning

Budgeting involves planning income and expenses to meet financial goals.

Financial planning includes:

Emergency funds

Insurance

Retirement planning

Long-term investments

Good planning improves financial stability and reduces uncertainty.

11. Liquidity

Liquidity refers to how easily an asset can be converted into cash.

Cash is the most liquid asset.

Real estate is less liquid.

Liquidity matters when quick access to money is needed.

12. Economic Cycles

Economies move through cycles:

Expansion

Peak

Recession

Recovery

Finance studies how these cycles affect employment, markets, inflation, and investment decisions.

Why these concepts matter

These ideas help individuals and organizations:

Make better financial decisions

Manage risk

Plan for the future

Understand how the economy functions

